:"1157","1123":"1123","1045":"1045","1254":"1254","after 1157":"efter 1157","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palæstina","Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England":"Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England","Spaldington, Bubwith, York, England":"Spaldington, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Compton, Sussex, England":"Compton, Sussex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"1123–7 May 1169":"1123–7 mei 1169","1123–1169":"1123–1169","1085–1123":"1085–1123","1160–1254":"1160–1254","1165–1204":"1165–1204","–1157":"–1157","1043–1123":"1043–1123","1045–1087":"1045–1087","7 May 1169":"7 mei 1169","1165":"1165","1087":"1087","1043":"1043","1085":"1085","1160":"1160","1204":"1204","1169":"1169","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1045":"1045","1254":"1254","after 1157":"na 1157","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestina","Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England":"Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England","Spaldington, Bubwith, York, England":"Spaldington, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Compton, Sussex, England":"Compton, Sussex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1123–7 May 1169":"1123–7 May 1169","1123–1169":"1123–1169","1085–1123":"1085–1123","1160–1254":"1160–1254","1165–1204":"1165–1204","–1157":"–1157","1043–1123":"1043–1123","1045–1087":"1045–1087","7 May 1169":"7 May 1169","1165":"1165","1087":"1087","1043":"1043","1085":"1085","1160":"1160","1204":"1204","1169":"1169","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1045":"1045","1254":"1254","after 1157":"after 1157","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine","Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England":"Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England","Spaldington, Bubwith, York, England":"Spaldington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Compton, Sussex, England":"Compton, Sussex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Haye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Willi.","North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from a personal name, Frisian <i>Hajo</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haio</i>; or from a short form of the female name <i>Hadewig</i>, composed of the elements <i>hadu</i> ‘battle, strife’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’.","German: variant of   Hey   4, 5."],"variants":[{"name":"Deshayes","meanings":["French: topographic name for someone who lived by an enclosure, from the plural of Old French <i>haye</i> ‘hedge’ (see   Haye   and   Hayes  ), with fused preposition and definite article <i>des</i> ‘from the’; or a habitational name denoting someone from Les Hayes, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Deshaies  ."]},{"name":"Hayenga","meanings":["East Frisian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Hajo</i> (see   Haye   1). It is formed with the suffix <i>-enga</i>, a variant of <i>-inga</i> (from the patronymic suffix <i>-ing</i> and genitive plural ending <i>-a</i>)."]},{"name":"Hey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Hay  .","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized (or archaic) and Flemish, of <b>Heij</b>, a topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, Dutch <i>hei</i>, <i>heide</i>.","German: metonymic occupational name for a grower or mower of grass, from Middle High German <i>höu</i> ‘grass, hay’."]},{"name":"Hayen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.  German Heinz, Wilhelm.","Flemish, East Frisian, and North German: patronymic from   Haye   1."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de la Haye was born in 1123, his father, Sir Ranulf Senesha Haye, was 80 and his mother, Olivia Albini, was 78. He had at least 4 sons with Muriel Lincoln. He died on 7 May 1169, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1123–7 May 1169":"1123–7. mai 1169","1123–1169":"1123–1169","1085–1123":"1085–1123","1160–1254":"1160–1254","1165–1204":"1165–1204","–1157":"–1157","1043–1123":"1043–1123","1045–1087":"1045–1087","7 May 1169":"7. mai 1169","1165":"1165","1087":"1087","1043":"1043","1085":"1085","1160":"1160","1204":"1204","1169":"1169","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1045":"1045","1254":"1254","after 1157":"pärast 1157","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestiina","Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England":"Brattleby, Lincolnshire, England","Spaldington, Bubwith, York, England":"Spaldington, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Compton, Sussex, England":"Compton, Sussex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1123–7 May 1169":"